CI/CD Pipeline Project using Jenkins Maven, Docker, Github Webhooks on AWS (Amazon Web Services)

Titus Diggs

·

6 min read
·
Nov 20, 2023

Creating a CI/CD pipeline involves coordinating different tools and procedures to enable continuous integration (CI) and continuous deployment/delivery (CD) of software. Here’s a breakdown of the setup with various commonly used tools:

1. Version Control System (VCS)

  • Tool: Git
  • Purpose: Manage code, track changes, and facilitate collaboration among developers.

2. CI/CD Server

  • Tool: Jenkins, CI/CD,
  • Purpose: Manage the pipeline, automate builds, tests, and deployments triggered by code changes.

3. Build Tools

  • Tool: Maven
  • Purpose: Compile code, handle dependencies, and generate executable artifacts.

4. Testing Frameworks

  • Tool: JUnit
  • Purpose: Automate and execute various tests (unit, integration, etc.) to ensure code quality.

5. Artifact Repository

  • Tool: JFrog Artifactory
  • Purpose: Store and manage build artifacts for sharing and deployment.

8 GB — → 40 GB and t2.micro → t2.large

Step 1: Create the EC2 instance in AWS account with these parameters.

EC2 type: Ubuntu t2.large

EBS → 40 GB

Region — → US-East-1

Step 2: Connect to EC2 and install all tools in the system as a root user.

To log in as a root user, use this command: (sudo su)

Step 3: Install Jenkins on Ubuntu with the below command. “Copy and paste the below command).”

#!/bin/bash
sudo apt update -y
sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install openjdk-17-jre -y
curl -fsSL https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable/jenkins.io-2023.key | sudo tee \
 /usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc > /dev/null
echo deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/jenkins-keyring.asc] \
 https://pkg.jenkins.io/debian-stable binary/ | sudo tee \
 /etc/apt/sources.list.d/jenkins.list > /dev/null
sudo apt-get update -y 
sudo apt-get install jenkins -y

Step 4: Change the security of the EC2 instance.

EC2 — -> Security groups — -> sg -000–000–00 — -> edit inbound rules and select the following: type → all traffic ->protocol all →port range →all →source →anywhere ipv4 → 0.0.0.0.0/0

Step 5: Sign into the Jenkins console.

https://<EC2_Public_IP>:8080 (8080 is the port number of jenkins)

Step 6: Get the administration password by hitting the below command in EC2 CLI.

Cat /var/lib/jenkins/secrets/initialAdminPassword

Step 7: Install all suggested plugins

Step 8: Create your first user.

Step 9: Create a pipeline job

Step 10: Add pipeline script as SCM (Source Code Management)

https://github.com/Trainedboy/Java_app_3.0.git

Step 10: Add the Plugins (In Jenkins Console)

← → Dashboard → Managed Jenkins — → Plugins — -> Available Plugins and the following plugins (Plugins for Sonar/Jfrog)

- Sonar Gerrit

- SonarQube Scanner

- SonarQube Generic Coverage

- Sonar Quality Gates

- Artifactory

  • Jfrog

Step 11: Setup docker with the following command

##Install in Amazon Ubuntu
#!/bin/bash
sudo apt update -y

sudo apt install apt-transport-https ca-certificates curl software-properties-common -y

curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg | sudo apt-key add -

sudo add-apt-repository "deb [arch=amd64] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu bionic stable" -y

sudo apt update -y

apt-cache policy docker-ce -y

sudo apt install docker-ce -y

#sudo systemctl status docker

sudo chmod 777 /var/run/docker.sock

Step 13: Install SonarQube with the below commands.

 docker run -d --name sonarqube -p 9000:9000 -p 9092:9092 sonarqube

Step 13.1: Start the docker container if it’s not up with the below command.

Docker ps -a (get the container ID)
docker start (container ID)

Step 13.2: Log into the sonar dashboard. (using the EC2 instance public IP and the port number for Sonarqube is 9000)

Username: admin

Password: admin

Step 13.3: Create a Sonar token for Jenkins.

SONAR DASHBOARD → ADMINISTRATION -> MY ACCOUNT — -> SECURITY — -> CREATE TOKEN — -> Save the token to some text file; we are going to need it later.

Step 13.4: Integrate Sonar into Jenkins

Sonar DASHBOARD — -> ADMINISTRATION — -> CONFIGURATION — -> WEBHOOKS — -> Add the below name and URL and save.

Name: “Use Jenkins or any name of your choice.”

https://<EC2_IP>:8080/sonarqube-webhooks/

Step 14: Install Maven with the below command

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install maven -y
mvn -version

STEP 15: INSTALL TRIVY FOR DOCKER IMAGE SCAN WITH THE BELOW COMMAND

# A Simple and Comprehensive Vulnerability Scanner for Containers and other Artifacts, Suitable for CI.

# A Simple and Comprehensive Vulnerability Scanner for Containers and other Artifacts, Suitable for CI.

sudo apt-get install wget apt-transport-https gnupg lsb-release
wget -qO - https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb/public.key | sudo apt-key add -
echo deb https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb $(lsb_release -sc) main | sudo tee -a /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install trivy

STEP 16: INTEGRATE ALL TOOLS WITH JENKINS

JENKINS DASHBOARD — -> MANAGE JENKINS — → CONFIGURE SYSTEM AND SEARCH FOR SONARQUBE INSTALLATIONS AND CLICK ON ADD SONARQUBE

STEP 16.1: CLICK ON SONARQUBE SERVERS  add url and name click on add token  select secret text  add the sonar token from step 13.1  give the name of the token as sonarqube-api.

STEP 17: ADD THE DOCKER HUB CREDENTIALS ID

JENKINS DASHBOARD  MANAGER JENKINS  CREDENTIALS  SEARCH FOR GLOBAL CREDENTIALS AND CLICK ADD CREDENTIALS

#Don’t forget to use your Docker credentials.

17.1 ADD THE DOCKER HUB CREDENTIALS WITH THE NAME DOCKER

STEP 18: ADD THE JENKINS SHARED LIBRARY

ON THE JENKINS DASHBOARD GO TO MANAGE JENKINS CONFIGURE SYSTEM GLOBAL PIPELINE LIBRARY ADD THE BELOW

NAME: my-shared-library

Default version: main

Git

https://github.com/trainedboy/jenkins_shared_lib.git

Step 19: once pipeline is run check for the following:

- The Jenkins log

- The Trivy scan vulnerabilities

  • The Sonarqube dashboard report
